    abstract = {{JWST has revealed a population of low-luminosity active galactic nuclei at z > 4 in compact, red hosts (the ``Little Red Dots,'' or LRDs), which are largely undetected in X-rays. We investigate this phenomenon using General Relativistic Radiation Magnetohydrodynamics simulations of super-Eddington accretion onto a supermassive black hole (SMBH) with M $\\\\\\_{{\textbullet}}$ = {}10$^{7}$ M $\\\\\\_{{\ensuremath{\odot}}}$ at z {\ensuremath{\sim}} 6, representing the median population; the spectral energy distributions (SEDs) that we obtain are intrinsically X-ray weak. The highest levels of X-ray weakness occur in SMBHs accreting at mildly super-Eddington rates (1.4 < f $\\\\\\_{Edd}$ < 4) with zero spin, viewed at angles >30{\textdegree} from the pole. X-ray bolometric corrections in the observed 2{\textendash}10 keV band reach {\ensuremath{\sim}}{}10$^{4}$ at z = 6, {\ensuremath{\sim}}5 times higher than the highest constraint from X-ray stacking. Most SEDs are extraordinarily steep and soft in the X-rays (median photon index {\ensuremath{\Gamma}} = 3.1, mode of {\ensuremath{\Gamma}} = 4.4). SEDs strong in the X-rays have harder spectra with a high-energy bump when viewed near the hot (>{}10$^{8}$ K) and highly relativistic jet, whereas X-ray weak SEDs lack this feature. Viewing an SMBH within 10{\textdegree} of its pole, where beaming enhances the X-ray emission, has a {\ensuremath{\sim}}1.5\\\\\\\% probability, matching the LRD X-ray detection rate. Next-generation observatories like AXIS will detect X-ray-weak LRDs at z {\ensuremath{\sim}} 6 from any viewing angle. Although many SMBHs in the LRDs are already estimated to accrete at super-Eddington rates, our model explains 50\\\\\\\% of their population by requiring that their masses are overestimated by a mere factor of {\ensuremath{\sim}}3. In summary, we suggest that LRDs host slowly spinning SMBHs accreting at mildly super-Eddington rates, with large covering factors and broad emission lines enhanced by strong winds, providing a self-consistent explanation for their X-ray weakness and complementing other models.}},
