    abstract = {{We study a sample of 14 spectroscopically confirmed Ly{\ensuremath{\alpha}} emitters (LAEs) in the late era of reionization (at redshift z {\ensuremath{\approx}} 6) based on the JWST/NIRCam imaging data set. These LAEs with high Ly{\ensuremath{\alpha}} luminosity of L(Ly{\ensuremath{\alpha}}) {\ensuremath{\sim}}10$^{42.4}${\textendash}10$^{43.4}$ erg s$^{‑1}$ have been covered by the (ongoing) COSMOS-Web survey over 0.28 deg$^{2}$ in four NIRCam bands (F115W, F150W, F277W, and F444W). With JWST/NIRCam imaging, we determine the UV continua with M $\\\\\\_{UV}$ ranging from ‑20.5 to ‑18.5 mag. The UV slopes have a median value of {\ensuremath{\beta}} {\ensuremath{\approx}} ‑2.35, and the steepest slopes can reach {\ensuremath{\beta}} < ‑3. Under the excellent spatial resolution of JWST, we identify three objects in the sample as potential merging/interacting systems. The 14 LAEs (and their components) are compact in morphology, residing substantially below the mass{\textendash}size relation of high-z galaxies. We further investigate their physical properties, including the stellar mass (M $\\\\\\_{*}$) and star formation rates (SFRs). Most of the LAEs lie on the SFR{\textendash}M $\\\\\\_{*}$ main-sequence relation, while two of them, featured as ``little red dots,'' likely host active galactic nuclei (AGNs), implying a {\ensuremath{\sim}}10\\\\\\\% AGN fraction. Moreover, we reveal that a new correlation may exist between Ly{\ensuremath{\alpha}} equivalent width and the offset between Ly{\ensuremath{\alpha}} and UV emission ({\ensuremath{\Delta}}d $\\\\\\_{Ly{\ensuremath{\alpha}} }$), with a median {\ensuremath{\Delta}}d $\\\\\\_{Ly{\ensuremath{\alpha}} }$ {\ensuremath{\sim}} 1 kpc. This could be explained by the Ly{\ensuremath{\alpha}} radiative transfer process in both the interstellar medium and circumgalactic medium. The results usher in a new era of detailed analysis on high-z LAEs with the JWST capability.}},
